WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.600
6-8 English

2
00:00:02.600 --> 00:00:05.400
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:11.800
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Phil

4
00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:13.200
And I'm Georgie

5
00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:20.200
If you're a swifty, that's a fan of Popstar Taylor Swift. Her music rocks your world

6
00:00:20.200 --> 00:00:26.200
I like that phrase rock your world Phil. It means that something makes your life enjoyable, right?

7
00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:33.200
Well, yes, but actually no Georgie. I mean Taylor Swift literally rocks the world

8
00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:43.200
At a recent concert in Edinburgh as part of Taylor Swift's Eros tour, her fans energetic dancing literally moved the earth

9
00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:49.200
With seismic activity usually associated with earthquakes detected four miles away

10
00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:55.000
Yes, it's hard to believe that in this program we'll be hearing about the swift quake

11
00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:00.000
A powerful force like an earthquake coming not from nature, but from a pop concert

12
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary as well

13
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:09.000
Great, but first I have a question for you Georgie

14
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:16.000
Actually, Taylor Swift's Edinburgh show wasn't the first music concert to trigger seismic waves

15
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
In 1992, the band Madness

16
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:25.000
It was two earthquakes that saw local residents evacuated from their homes

17
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:31.000
But at which London venue did the concert take place? Was it a, hide park?

18
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:36.000
B, the Royal Albert Hall or C, Finns Repark?

19
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
I'll guess the concert was held at the Royal Albert Hall

20
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Okay, Georgie, I'll reveal the correct answer at the end of the program

21
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:52.000
Following Taylor Swift's Edinburgh concert, seismologist Emma Greener and James Pantern from Cardiff University

22
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Wanted to see if the same thing would happen at Taylor's concert in Cardiff

23
00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
seismologists are scientists who study earthquakes and seismic waves

24
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Emma and James set up their equipment to monitor and record ground motion as the concert got started

25
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:14.000
As James explains here to Marny Chesterton, presenter of BBC Radio 4 program Inside Science

26
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:19.000
Tell me about the peak on this graph that you're seeing and what that actually corresponds to

27
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:26.000
In this top graph of the red wiggly line, we're looking at the ground velocity in essentially meters per second

28
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
So that's the velocity that the ground is vibrating up and down

29
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
So this is literally people stamping up and down

30
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Yes, this is all of the energy combined from the 75,000 people in the stadium

31
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.000
Jumping in unison and stamping in unison

32
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:48.000
James, the British geological survey recorded 23.4 nanometers of movement in Edinburgh

33
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:49.000
What does that actually mean?

34
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:59.000
So what that means is that they recorded the ground flexing up and down by a distance of 23 nanometers

35
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.000
James's equipment recorded seismic movement when Taylor Swift started to sing

36
00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Her hit song, Croll Summer, created a peak, the highest point in the graph which James's machine was drawing

37
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:17.000
The peak was made by thousands of Swifties jumping up and down in unison together and at the same time

38
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:20.000
Creating something like a mini earthquake

39
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:25.000
The seismologists measured a ground movement of 23 nanometers

40
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:32.000
That may not sound much, but remember this is the earth itself actually flexing or bending without breaking

41
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:38.000
So the ground is shaking, music is blasting and thousands of fans are dancing

42
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
But does this qualify as an earthquake scientifically speaking?

43
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:48.000
Here's James Panton and Marny Chesterton again for BBC Radio 4's Inside Science

44
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:53.000
James, impressive as this is to see coming up on your seismograph

45
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
This is not the same league really as an earthquake

46
00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:58.000
No, definitely not

47
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:04.000
There have been some people who have tried to convert the energy output from concerts

48
00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Into a local magnitude scale to make it comparable to an earthquake

49
00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:14.000
And when that's happened, we find magnitude that are generally less than one

50
00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
Sadly, the answer to Gorge's question is no

51
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.000
The Taylor Swift concert wasn't technically an earthquake

52
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:26.000
Marny says the concert was not in the same league

53
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Meaning not nearly as good or important as something else

54
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Yes, the energy created by the music sound waves and thousands of fans jumping

55
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:42.000
Did move the earth, but not in a way that's comparable or similar to a real earthquake

56
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:46.000
By definition, an earthquake must break the earth's crust

57
00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:51.000
And is caused by either the movement of tectonic plates or a volcano

58
00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Officially Taylor Swift didn't cause an earthquake

59
00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
But for the Swifties, it probably felt like one

60
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
All of which brings us back to my question, Gorge

61
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
I asked you about another earth shattering concert involving the British band Madness

62
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:09.000
But where inland did the show take place

63
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.000
And I guessed it was at the Royal Albert Hall

64
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Which was the wrong answer I'm afraid, Gorge, in fact the concert happened in Finsbury Park

65
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learnt in this program

66
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Starting with the phrase, Rock Your World

67
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
Meaning that someone or something has a positive effect on you

68
00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Making your life enjoyable

69
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
A peak is the highest point of something

70
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:38.000
When things happen in unison, they happen together at the same time

71
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
To flex means to bend without breaking

72
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
If you say something is not in the same league as something else

73
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:49.000
You mean it's nowhere near as good or important

74
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:55.000
And finally the adjective comparable means similar in size, amount or quality

75
00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.000
Once again, our six minutes are up

76
00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:02.000
But remember to join us again next time for more trending topics and useful vocabulary

77
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Here at six-minute English, goodbye for now

78
